commit.message: Fixed a few small bugs/mistakes.

Wrote a new Collections API based on Java's and with map-like functions like in JS.

It uses inheritance for its interfaces, but its implementations are composition-based.
All methods are bound.

All Collections optionally require a HashEquals<T, H = number | string>,
which hashes an element of type T to type H, which defaults to number or string.
It defaults to HashEquals.default(), which uses referential equality and JSON.stringify to hash.

So far, only ArrayStack, HashMap, and HashSet are implemented.

Collection.basedOn() is used for composition "inheritance".

Ran into some nasty problems with the TypeScript type system:
    No higher kinded types, so a generic type parameter can't be generic itself.
    No contra/covariance, only bivariance in generics.
    keyof doesn't include well known symbols (e.x. Symbol.iterator),
       meaning Difference<T, U> = U \ T (set difference) doesn't fully work.

Made Route and Test have Rules like Router,
i.e., Route has RouteRule like how Router has RouterRule.

The Rule versions, and their derivatives like UnTypedRules,
are usually simple POJOs and thus serializable.

There are now also Route and Test constructors,
which mainly take a string or function input (regex for Test too).
The string versions use the given string literal,
and the function versions use a user-provided function called through the Sandbox.

Added a bunch of Array extension methods like
mapFilter, asyncMap, asyncFilter, and asyncMapFilter.
mapFilter calls map and then filters by truthiness (see Truthy.ts).
The async versions do the same but use callbacks that return Promises
and deal with all the weird ways to do it, including the types.

TODO

Perhaps refactor the Ruleable types (Router, Route, Test)
into a metafactory since there is so much common code and related interfaces.
However, it's pretty complicated with all the generated type relationships,
so unless I create a lot more Ruleable types in the future,
I'll leave this alone for a while.

Fix the input UI, maybe in EditableRule.

Add a (Ruleable) post download action of sorts,
meaning after the download, an action can be performed,
such as opening the file, deleting it from the download history, etc.

Add an option for a download route to cancel a download
(perhaps part of the above idea).

For inputting user-defined functions,
use an embedded online IDE with TypeScript intellisense like StackBlitz,
which is based off of Visual Studio Code.
This should be really nice if it works.

If I can get the user-defined functions set up well,
we should also allow the user to define new Routers
purely in JS like how I'm doing so right now in sampleRules.ts.

Wrote Sandbox.ts (the sandbox)
and SandboxMessenger.ts (the client communicating with the sandbox).
They communicate using Window.postMessage()
and supposedly allow you to use eval, which is unsafe,
b/c it's in a sandbox, which has no access to Chrome APIs.

SandboxMessenger exposes to methods: evaluate() and compile().

evaluate(string) evaluates a string directly as JS
and async returns its value.

compile(string) evaluates a string that should be a function
and async returns a function proxy to it.
The actual function cannot be serialized over postMessage(),
but a reference via a unique ID is maintained,
so that when the function proxy is called with arguments (or bind() is called),
it sends the arguments to the sandbox via postMessage() where the function is called,
and then the result is return async to the client.

It all works when I run it not as a Chrome extension,
but even though eval() (really new Function()) is being called in the safe sandbox,
it's still throwing an error that I'm violating the CSP,
even though I specified the sandbox's CSP should allow unsafe eval.

I'm not sure how to fix this.

Setup Webpack to compile sandbox.html and PolybiusSandbox.js,
which will run all sandboxed code.

Since eval doesn't work in the background script
due to the extension's content security policy (CSP),
I need to run eval in a sandboxed page
and then communicate with the background page using window.postMessage().

I didn't set up the JS/TS code for this yet,
but I set up the Webpack compilation for it.

Also, WebAssembly.compile(), etc. violate the CSP, too, so that's not an option either.

Typed Function.bind() when only the thisArg is supplied,
in which case it returns a function of the same type.

Added a chrome.storage.onChanged listener that refreshes any StorageItem that was updated.

This is done by adding a refreshers field to StorageImpl,
which is called with the StorageChanges when there is a change.

Each StorageItem adds a refresher to its StorageImpl.refreshers,
which checks if its StorageKey is in the StorageChanges,
and if it is, calls its own refreshers.

Modified Callables and Callable to be
Callables<T = undefined> and Callable<T = undefined>.
This allows an argument to be passed to each Callable and Callables.call(),
or none if T = undefined.
This does require some trickery with the type system to make this work, though,
but the implementation is sound.

Got RegExp tests to work fully.
I tested it with /^.*google.*$/i for Url Href and it works.

Changed value prop to defaultValue in <input>s, which makes them editable.
When using value, it makes them read only, which isn't what we want.

Added chrome.storage APIs in Storages.
The default StorageImpl in StorageItem is now Storages.chrome.sync.

Added Object.getPrototypeChain()
and refactored Object.getAllPropertyNames() using it.

Fixed Object.getAllPropertyNames() to include Object.prototype,
which fixed bind() to bind those methods, too.

Cleaned up, refactored, and extended a lot of stuff.

The actual extension (including manifest.json) are now in dist/.
This gets rid of the key file errors and dramatically reduces the extension size,
since node_modules/ isn't in the extension anymore.

Renamed RouterOptions to RouterRule and any names like it.

Renamed DownloadRouter to just Router.

Renamed Prompt to ConflictingRules.

Moved the onDeterminingFilename listener to downloadListener.ts.

Refactored RouterRule interfaces, etc. from Router.ts into RouterRule.ts.

Refactored the sample rules in Router.ts to sampleRules.ts.

Refactored Path from Router.ts to util/Path.ts.
Added util/polyfills/path.ts to merge "path" and "path-browserify" packages.

Refactored Test interface from Router.ts to util/functional/Test.ts.

Refactored DownloadRoute and DownloadAction from Router.ts to DownloadRoute.ts.

Added referrer and mimeType RouterConstructors in Router.

Enabled RegExps in input tests.
If the inputted string is a RegExp literal, that is /<pattern>/<flags>,
then the test function is that RegExp.boundTest().
If not, then the test function is just string equality.
TODO: We should have an indicator if the current input is a valid RegExp in the form.

Removed getRouterRules(), setRouterRules(), and getRouters() from serialize.ts.
Now serialize.ts just contains the serialization/conversion functions.
These methods are replaced in Storage.ts.

Added Storages.ts, which contains standardized interfaces (StorageImpl)
for accessing different Chrome storage APIs,
such as localStorage, sessionStorage, and chrome.storage.sync (TODO).
These can be simply accessed using Storage.local, etc.

Added StorageItem.ts, which contains the StorageItem class.
A StorageItem has two methods: get() and set(value),
which are both async and get and set the value of the item
from the underlying storage.
get() and set() are both cached.

StorageItem has two factory methods: newObject() and newArray().

newObject<T, U = T>(): StorageItem<T> takes
   a storageImpl: StorageImpl, the underlying storage interface,
   a storageKey: StorageKey, a key of Storage (in Storage.ts),
   a defaultValue: T, the default value to set in the storage if nothing is there yet,
   a serializer: Serializer<T, string>, which converts T to a string and back.
The serializer defaults to jsonSerializer(), which uses JSON.stringify and JSON.parse.
An optional converter: Serializer<T, U> can be used, too,
   in which case serializer: Serializer<U, string>.
   This allows you to convert T to an intermediate U than can be directly serialized,
   usually by jsonSerializer().
   This is useful when T contains complex methods/objects,
   so it can be converted to U which is just a POJO.

newArray<T, U = T>() is similar to newObject(), except it returns a StorageItems<T> instead.
StorageItems<T> = StorageItem<T[]>, so it's used when you want to store a T[].
The converter argument is changed to act on each T instead of the whole array.
The whole array mapped using the converter is then serialized using serializer.
There is no defaultValue (the underlying newObject() defaultValue is []).

Both StorageItem and StorageItems contain a map() method,
which takes a downstream (bi-)mapper function (a Serializer).
StorageItem<T>.map(mapper: Serializer<U, T>): StorageItem<U>.
StorageItems<T>.map(mapper: Serializer<U, T>): StorageItems<U>.
Using the mapper function, this creates a new StorageItem(s)
of type U that uses the serializer to convert back and forth from the mapped U.
For example, routerRules: StorageItems<RouterRule>
can be mapped to routers: StorageItems<Router> by using a serializer
that converts between RouterRule and Router.

Since the mapped StorageItem(s) depend on each other,
calling set() on any one will invalidate the caches of the others.
Therefore, each StorageItem contains a refresher: Callables,
which is called on every set() to refresh all the caches.

Callables is basically a Callable[], where Callable = () => void.
It contains an add(Callable) method
and a call() method that calls all the callables.
Each mapped StorageItem shares the same refresher: Callables.
When a new StorageItem is mapped,
it's refresh function (cache invalidator) is added to refreshers: Callables.

Added storage in Storage.ts,
which maps StorageKeys to StorageItem(s)s
and contains their implementations,
with the serializers being imported from serialize.ts.

Since storage[StorageKey].get() is now async,
the download listener must be async, too,
but the Chrome API doesn't allow this directly.
The listener remains synchronous,
but returns true to indicate suggest will be called async.
An async IIFE is then used to call await storage.routers.get()
and make then call suggest.

Ported @named(string) in util/decorators/named.ts.

Added @bindClass in util/decorators/bind.ts,
which binds all methods of a class to the actual constructed object.

This uses bind<T>(T) in bind.ts,
which binds all the methods in the entire prototype chain of T.

typeAliases.ts contains type aliases for es6, which are automatically imported.
Thus, when I overwrite the name of an es6 and can no longer access,
I can instead import the type alias in typeAliases.ts.
So far, I've done this for BrowserStorage = Storage,
since Storage.ts defines the Storage interface.

Most of these changes don't add any new features (except for RegExp support),
but it makes everything a lot more robust and extendable.
For example, using Storages, a StorageImpl from chrome.storage.sync can be added,
which stores data in the cloud and thus allow you to sync across a user's many computers.

bind() is also immensely useful.

Multiple matches work now, too. It just chooses the first match.
